Rearranging $x^2 - x - 1= 0$ gives $x^2 = x + 1$.  So, repeatedly substituting $x+1$ for $x^2$ gives us \begin{align*}
x^3 - 2x + 1 &= x(x^2)-2x + 1\\
&=x(x+1) - 2x + 1\\
&= x^2 + x -2x + 1\\
&= x^2 - x + 1\\
&= (x+1) - x + 1\\
&=\boxed{2}
\end{align*}

Recall that $a^m\div a^n=a^{m-n}$ for positive integers $m>n$ and $a^m\cdot a^n=a^{m+n}$. Now we can write $5^5\div5^4-5^3+5^2\cdot5^1$ as $5^1-5^3+5^3$. Using the definition of subtraction and the associative property of addition, we get \begin{align*}
5^1-5^3+5^3&=5^1+-5^3+5^3\\
&=5^1+(-5^3+5^3)\\
&=5^1+0\\
&=\boxed{5}.
\end{align*}

We may carry out long division in base 5 just as in base 10. We have  \[
\begin{array}{c|ccc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{2} & 0 & 4 \\
\cline{2-4}
2 & 4 & 1 & 3 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{4} & \downarrow & \\ \cline{2-2}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & 1 & \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & \downarrow \\ \cline{3-3}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 1 & 3 \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 1 & 3 \\ \cline{3-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & 0
\end{array}
\]for a quotient of $\boxed{204_5}$. Note that in the above calculation we have used that $13_5$ divided by $2_5$ is $4_5$, which follows from $4_5\times2_5=8_{10}=13_5$.

Each of the five marked angles measures $360/5=72$ degrees, so $\boxed{72}$ degrees is the minimum angle through which the pentagon may be rotated so that it coincides with its original position.

